{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7d734c55-0d98-484f-85d8-a5c248db2c8c","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the rundown:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID strategy** from the legacy short name to a fully-qualified name (`Namespace.Class.Method`). Azure DevOps keys history on this ID, so every test looks \"new.\"\n\n**Fix** — add this to your `.csproj` (or `Directory.Build.props`) to restore the old IDs:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4 the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level** context — no individual test is running yet, so `TestName` throws. In v3 it silently returned the name of the first test that happened to trigger initialization, which was misleading.\n\n**Fix for your code** — remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit`:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Move per-test logging to [TestInitialize] instead\n}\n```\n\nIf you need a per-test name during setup, use `[TestInitialize]`:\n\n```csharp\n[TestInitialize]\npublic void TestInit()\n{\n    var testName = TestContext.TestName; // works fine here\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 things to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` on doubles** | Tolerance comparison tightened; previously-passing float tests may fail |\n| **Parallelization** | Class-level parallelism is now **on by default**; tests with shared state may break — add `[Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or `[DoNotParallelize]` as needed |\n| **`[Timeout]`** | Now uses `CancellationToken` co-operative cancellation instead of `Thread.Abort`; long-running tests that ignore the token may no longer be killed |\n| **`TestContext.WriteLine`** | Thread-safe in v4, but output ordering may differ from v3 |\n| **Removed APIs** | `TestContext.DataConnection`, `TestContext.DataRow` (legacy data-driven) are removed |\n\n---\n\nWant me to apply the fixes to your project files?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cbb55aac-6b06-4cdf-a87a-ab7db77fe6d3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide a comprehensive answer based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes.\n\nKey breaking changes in MSTest v4:\n\n1. **Fully qualified test ID by default** — MSTest v4 changed the default test ID to use fully qualified names (namespace + class + method). This causes ADO/Azure DevOps to see every test as \"new\" since the IDs changed. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` to `Legacy` or understand this is the new default.\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a \"class-level\" context, not tied to any specific test. \n\nAccessing `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]` now throws an exception since there's no actual test running at that initialization point—this change makes the semantics clearer about what context is available. Beyond that, there are shifts in default parallelization behavior, how `DeploymentItem` works, and changes to `DataRow` and `DynamicData` handling, plus adjustments to the ordering of cleanup and initialization methods.","outputTokens":945,"requestId":"3403:11A36E:1034EFE:12F03E0:69F41550"},"id":"bcf57773-5b8f-4a44-a89a-54ee304155db","timestamp":"2026-05-01T02:52:20.806Z","parentId":"bcf94ad9-2484-49ea-ac53-e08938b45064"}
